Assembling February 7, 2014!

"The LEGOÂ® Movie," the first-ever, full-length theatrical LEGOÂ® adventure, directed by Phil Lord & Christopher Miller, opens in theaters February 7, 2014. It stars the vocal talents of Chris Pratt, Will Ferrell, Elizabeth Banks, Will Arnett, Nick Offerman and Alison Brie, with Liam Neeson and Morgan Freeman.

The original 3D computer animated story follows Emmet, an ordinary, rules-following, perfectly average LEGO minifigure who is mistakenly identified as the most extraordinary person and the key to saving the world. Title: The LEGOÂ® Movie - Official Main Trailer [HD]
Comment:
Warner Brothers can kiss my cold ass because all this movie was attempting was first - to attract young viewers and get money from that, and to also use CGI techniques to make a fake stop motion movie, to where it looks like stop motion, so everyone thinks it is. Since this one looks so good with its fake CGI, people think that it is real, and think everyone sucks, when really people put a lot of time into it. Knowing that, everyone's stop motions who are doing REAL stop motion and doing good get 30% more dislikes and hate after the Lego Movie was released. It was all a marketing technique to attract more views and likings towards The Lego Movie.  

As a stop motion animator, I can confirm the changes in ratings. I remember first doing stop motion back in 2013, in the summer, when this was introduced. Everything was all fun and games, no one even made money, and everyone loved this new stop motion hit on youtube, then The Lego Movie was released, and all the viewers now liking Legos from the stop motion videos, saw that, thought it was stop motion which it WASN'T, and then hated all the real stuff that people put work in, then compared, people are like "This is terrible compared to the Lego Movie", yeah but before then, it was that video that you (in general) said was your favorite...

Comment:
seemed like a cartoon movie which gives joy only, but in fact (after watching the movie) there are many truths in it. giving general problems of our life (lord business etc.) and also individual things. 
beside, the main message was quite important, it is strongly connected to what i've studied in Sociology course last year. Thomas Theorem states that 'if men define a situation as real, it is real in its consequences'. when Emmet believed that he was special, he made it he's own reality and in fact as a consequence, he made real special things (self-fulfilling prophecy is also a term in sociology connected to this)
basicly and generally: you are what you think of yourself.
but after all, it was quite funny movie too. the dialogues and the way they made characters speak is quite cool. isn't it the best for a movie to mix funny things and realities?

Title: The LEGOÂ® Movie - Official Main Trailer [HD]
Comment: Between the fits laughter, there was only one thing I could think about while watching this movie: How did they get away with this? How did they take what could have easily been a glorified toy commercial and make it one of the most clever, funny and surprisingly loving and poignant movies in recent memory. I don't even know if I can complain that the trailers are doing a bit of a poor job of selling just how brilliant this movie is, because it makes the surprise all that more pronounced. For anyone who loved or still loves LEGO and the idea and concept that stands at its core, don't miss out on this. It's so true and earnest to the "source material" that I still can't help but be amazed that it was made at all. Bravo, bravo.

Title: The LEGOÂ® Movie - Official Main Trailer [HD]
Comment: The Lego Movie is hilarious! We loved how clever and witty it was. We never imagined it to be a reflection of our culture, how people have conformed to corporatism and indoctrinated programming. The idea of a lego (Emmit) who begins questioning things, joins forces with a cool chick (Wild Style), and breaks away from conformism to embrace independent thought and change was refreshing and fun. My only gripe was that the message gets lost in the overwhelming spectacle, and almost contradicts what the film rallies against at one point, when the legos conform in order to break into Lord Business's chambers. The writer's could have found a more creative way IMO. Otherwise, the movie remains funny and inventive throughout. They really took their time to make a great film for both kids and adults to enjoy. Well done!

Title: The LEGOÂ® Movie - Official Main Trailer [HD]
Comment:
Yeah, just watched that movie, i thought it couldn't be that good, being about legos, but it was actually far beyond my expectations, i expected some "cheesy crap", but it was actually quite good, and the humour was perfect (to me anyway), scenario isn't top-notch (a bit clichÃ© i'd say), but it's more than decent, bit of music here and there, references, fluid animation and the usual more or less subtle "moral" stuff you get in any family animation movie, it's as much worth as the big titles in the animation/family category you would see made by studios like dreamwork. IMO.
It's a light-hearted movie, good for some laugh or entertaining. Of course it's not a masterpiece made by your "good ol' classic 20th century producer", and some people are just harder to satisfy than i am, even tho i can be kinda bitchy myself. But i enjoyed it as much as i would have for a good movie in it's kind, though it seemed more targeted at teenagers than any other audience, still can be watched with friends or family.

"Unexpectedly good", That's what i'd call this movie. Don't expect TOO much from it, but don't let the "cover" (and super-bitchy people) turn you away from a potentially good movie.

Title: The LEGOÂ® Movie - Official Main Trailer [HD]
Comment: Surprisingly this movie while it had so many overused cliche`s,plot devices and character archetypes that we`ve seen time and time before it still delivered soo much fun and creativity all the way down to the animation. Probably because the characters while cliche were very likable and have tons of moments and scenes to shine and show off their personalities. For example bad cop is the usual henchman that you know is going to turn good at the end. But they gave him some nice redeemable qualities and a good cop side to him that you can`t help but Â like him. Plus whenever the movie was in fact going to fall in a usual cliche they made fun of it in a very clever way. And finally I just love how that twist in the end (which I`m not giving away for obvious reasons) actually justifies every single one of the stereotypes in the movie where it makes complete sense. It`s a very thoughtful message. Just be yourself!! Don`t just limit yourself to what the instructions tell you. And I guess that with Lego`s this is the perfect way to give this message to your kids. They`ll really be able to connect to this.

Comment:
In most cases, there tends to be that one film that defines your childhood a...nd in many of those cases in my generation, that film would most likely be Toy Story. Well, I feel privileged to have not one, but two define mine. It's incredible how my childhood was defined at the beginning with Toy Story, then grew up alongside PIXAR and then be reminded of that beginning eleven years later with Toy Story 3. But on the verge of the end of my childhood, it seemed rather fitting for it to end with a movie that reminded me of what I enjoyed most off-screen. LEGO. I felt more of a child than I've ever felt in recent years watching this movie and couldn't ask anything more from it. It was truly incredible and I never wanted it to end.
THIS is my newÂ favourite movie

Comment:
I don't care that it's immature, and I don't care that this is "for children". Who says that childhood has to end? Yes, real life obviously takes real work, but what's life without the living? What's a salary worth without joy? Life doesn't end at 18, and I don't care what you think! I'm gonna watch funny movies and have snowball fights and roll down hills and watch the clouds and pretend I'm on the International Space Station. I'm gonna use the word "gonna" in a blatant run-on sentence too. Why? Because life is about living. Sure, I'll go get my degree... but then I'll enjoy the life I've been given. I don't want to let my life collect dust on the shelves. What's the gain? Your money won't follow you when you're gone. I don't know about you, but I'd rather stockpile a little happiness while I'm here. I choose to live while I'm alive.

Long story short, to those who know who they are, stop pretending to be holier than the rest of us for stifling your happiness to please the strangers. Go out and live a little, okay?

He trudged through the ankle-deep snow, his hands in his pockets and his eyes on his shoes. Fallen snow stuck in his wavy hair and his eyelashes. He was was walking away from the worst day of his life. He looked back on these past few days...

He had first seen her walking down this very block block months ago, her long dark hair flecked with drops of rain. He had been starstruck when he saw her, and ran through the deluge or rain, trying to catch up with her. She turned a corner. He followed. When he caught up to her, he was breathless. She smiled at him as he gasped for air. Then she turned into the coffee shop. He sat at the booth while she was working behind the counter. He couldn't stop looking at her. After a while, he managed to walk up to the counter and ask her name.Â 
Soon, after about three weeks of watching her work, he asked her out.Â 

The next few months were bliss. They hung out at the coffee shop. He bought her flowers, and were almost inseparable. But it was not to last. She had gone on a trip. He stayed home and didn't go anywhere while she was away, pacing. He texted her all the time, sending her little messages to stay in touch. When she was getting on to the plane to come home, she told him she couldn't text him while she was on the plane. He paced even more because he didn't even have her texts to keep him occupied.Â 

He had texted her when she was supposed to get off the plane. No reply. He tried not to panic, and turned on the tv to get his mind off it. On the channel he normally watched there was a huge news story instead of the normal programming: PLANE WRECK SLAUGHTERS THOUSANDS. His heart started to beat faster with panic. The reporter had said that the plane was coming back from where she had gone on her trip, and that no one had survived. She had been on that plane. He was in shock. But somewhere in the back of his brain told him that it couldn't be true. He ran through the snowstorm outside towards the airport, forgetting everything, just trying to see her, to see if she was really...

He arrived at the airport. A multitude of people were there. Most of them were asking the same question as he was, "Is it true?" "Did any survive?" "Where are they?" But they were all gone, all wiped out at the same time, no survivors. This is where we are now, walking through the snow, him trying to forget, missing her so much, but knowing that she will never reply to his texts, and that she was never coming back to him.
